tasks.description:
### WOW moments: This is ONLY possible with AI assistance
- User flow: Can you restructure my task list so that all outstanding items in the giskard project move to a backlog task?

- Push: Daily updates
Set up push notifications for daily review (here’s how yesterday went, here are some ideas for today). 
This will help users stay on track with their productivity goals.

this is a prioritisation tool. Ideally there would be some sense that tasks still exist somewhere as context for the LLM the next time something needs to get done. But if it’s not needed today, I dont need to see it.

### I *personally* really want
- better “completed” status
4 tasks completed today → Split into [health]: 1, [career]: 2, [learning]: 1

- Ability for giskard to fix old tasks (e.g. I completed x today in the ui, but actually it was yesterdays task)

- How should we implement projects?

> I'm having trouble connecting right now. Please check if Ollama is running with llama3.1:8b and try again

- Why does drag and drop fail to initialise sometimes?!

- Fix ‘undo’ in chat to only appear when relevant

- How should we display past chats and/or completed tasks?
Implement history for completed tas

tasks.title: Investigate ‘small models’ white paper
tasks.description:
Note here: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1SV8yb9ykEr3g7jpun6Q5zsAy_myeiosjRI_2s-bo0K8/edit?tab=t.76zo52631itx
NVIDIA Small Models White Paper — Key Points
Core Thesis
Small language models (SLMs, < ~10B parameters) are good enough for many agentic AI tasks.


They offer major advantages in latency, cost, and deployability, making them better suited for large-scale, production agent systems.


LLMs remain necessary for open-ended reasoning and novel situations, but shouldn’t run every part of the pipeline.


Advantages of SLMs
Cost — inference is cheaper by 10–50× compared to LLMs.


Speed — lower latency makes interactive/real-time use feasible.


Deployability — easier to run on local or edge hardware; simpler to fine-tune and swap in/out.


Sustainability — reduced energy and infra burden.


Hybrid Architecture
Use SLMs for repetitive, structured errands (tool calls, JSON generation, routing, summarization).


Use LLMs as a fallback for high-novelty or ambiguous cases.


Goal: modular, composable agent pipelines where SLMs handle most traffic.


Conversion Process (LLM → SLM)
Collect logs of LLM usage.


Cluster recurring “agentic errands.”


Train or fine-tune SLMs per cluster.


Swap SLMs into pipeline with LLM fallback.


Iterate with evaluation and guardrails.


Barriers to Adoption
Ecosystem inertia: infra and culture built around LLMs.


Evaluation bias: benchmarks reward broad reasoning, favoring LLMs.


Trust gap: SLMs more brittle on edge cases, hallucinations more visible.


Operational complexity: orchestration with multiple models adds moving parts.


Risks & Limitations
Over-specialization can cause brittle failure on distribution shift.


Benchmarks may under-reflect real agentic workloads.


Without fallback/abstain mechanisms, errors can be catastrophic.


Takeaway
For agentic AI, small is beautiful: push high-volume, structured tasks to SLMs, reserve LLMs for rare or novel reasoning.


This hybrid approach reduces cost and latency while enabling new product patterns (continuous background checks, near-real-time monitoring)

tasks.description:
Notes from meetup:

PM in the Age of AI — Meetup Recap

Attendees: Derek, Geoff (ProductCamp), Nate, Jason, Adele (joined later), Charles.
Theme: How product management changes in the age of AI.

⸻

Market & Culture
	•	Jason: Compared US and Asia tech approaches.
	•	Asia: relentless execution and incrementalism.
	•	US: divergent exploration.
	•	Lens for adoption: execution focus vs divergent experimentation.

⸻

Talent Shape with AI
	•	AI won’t outperform top experts, and it won’t rescue the weakest.
	•	It primarily lifts the middle 90%.
	•	Shapes:
	•	T-shape → V-shape: AI makes you deeper in adjacent areas and broader overall.
	•	Debate: does it create a “bigger T” or a “sharper V”?
	•	Charles: personal sense is that AI sharpens into a V-shape.

⸻

Product Practice with AI
	•	PRDs → Prototypes: Faster validation cycles.
	•	Derek: Example GTM tools: Amplemarket + Clay.
	•	Feedback to Charles:
	•	Prototypes = forcing function + communication tool.
	•	Last mile remains:
	•	Quick Start docs at beginning + “Things to watch for” docs at end help.
	•	LLM prototypes: useful to say “close to vision, not worth fixing yet.”

⸻

LLM Risks & Controls
	•	More reasoning steps + more tool hops = higher drift risk.
	•	Strong PM oversight can control drift but can’t eliminate it.
	•	Some challenges remain structural:
	•	Example: PRDs still useful for handover across teams.
	•	AI can’t fix cultural or ownership gaps.

⸻

“AI Insights” Caveat
	•	AI often averages → results can feel like design-by-committee.
	•	Good reminder: don’t outsource expert judgment.

⸻

Giskard Demo Feedback
	•	Time & Events focus:
	•	Use calendar as input to log.
	•	Use calendar for time-blocking (“spend 20 mins on X”).
	•	Explore automatic task creation from events.
	•	Light gamification may help.
	•	Stickiness of calendars:
	•	Calendars = socially enforced (invitations).
	•	Avoid task backlog; calendar is always “blank.”
	•	Context engineering:
	•	Stronger data access + integration with note-takers.

⸻

tasks.title: Investigate ‘small models’ white paper
tasks.description:
Note here: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1SV8yb9ykEr3g7jpun6Q5zsAy_myeiosjRI_2s-bo0K8/edit?tab=t.76zo52631itx
NVIDIA Small Models White Paper — Key Points
Core Thesis
Small language models (SLMs, < ~10B parameters) are good enough for many agentic AI tasks.


They offer major advantages in latency, cost, and deployability, making them better suited for large-scale, production agent systems.


LLMs remain necessary for open-ended reasoning and novel situations, but shouldn’t run every part of the pipeline.


Advantages of SLMs
Cost — inference is cheaper by 10–50× compared to LLMs.


Speed — lower latency makes interactive/real-time use feasible.


Deployability — easier to run on local or edge hardware; simpler to fine-tune and swap in/out.


Sustainability — reduced energy and infra burden.


Hybrid Architecture
Use SLMs for repetitive, structured errands (tool calls, JSON generation, routing, summarization).


Use LLMs as a fallback for high-novelty or ambiguous cases.


Goal: modular, composable agent pipelines where SLMs handle most traffic.


Conversion Process (LLM → SLM)
Collect logs of LLM usage.


Cluster recurring “agentic errands.”


Train or fine-tune SLMs per cluster.


Swap SLMs into pipeline with LLM fallback.


Iterate with evaluation and guardrails.


Barriers to Adoption
Ecosystem inertia: infra and culture built around LLMs.


Evaluation bias: benchmarks reward broad reasoning, favoring LLMs.


Trust gap: SLMs more brittle on edge cases, hallucinations more visible.


Operational complexity: orchestration with multiple models adds moving parts.


Risks & Limitations
Over-specialization can cause brittle failure on distribution shift.


Benchmarks may under-reflect real agentic workloads.


Without fallback/abstain mechanisms, errors can be catastrophic.


Takeaway
For agentic AI, small is beautiful: push high-volume, structured tasks to SLMs, reserve LLMs for rare or novel reasoning.


This hybrid approach reduces cost and latency while enabling new product patterns (continuous background checks, near-real-time monitoring)

tasks.description:
Notes from meetup:

PM in the Age of AI — Meetup Recap

Attendees: Derek, Geoff (ProductCamp), Nate, Jason, Adele (joined later), Charles.
Theme: How product management changes in the age of AI.

⸻

Market & Culture
	•	Jason: Compared US and Asia tech approaches.
	•	Asia: relentless execution and incrementalism.
	•	US: divergent exploration.
	•	Lens for adoption: execution focus vs divergent experimentation.

⸻

Talent Shape with AI
	•	AI won’t outperform top experts, and it won’t rescue the weakest.
	•	It primarily lifts the middle 90%.
	•	Shapes:
	•	T-shape → V-shape: AI makes you deeper in adjacent areas and broader overall.
	•	Debate: does it create a “bigger T” or a “sharper V”?
	•	Charles: personal sense is that AI sharpens into a V-shape.

⸻

Product Practice with AI
	•	PRDs → Prototypes: Faster validation cycles.
	•	Derek: Example GTM tools: Amplemarket + Clay.
	•	Feedback to Charles:
	•	Prototypes = forcing function + communication tool.
	•	Last mile remains:
	•	Quick Start docs at beginning + “Things to watch for” docs at end help.
	•	LLM prototypes: useful to say “close to vision, not worth fixing yet.”

⸻

LLM Risks & Controls
	•	More reasoning steps + more tool hops = higher drift risk.
	•	Strong PM oversight can control drift but can’t eliminate it.
	•	Some challenges remain structural:
	•	Example: PRDs still useful for handover across teams.
	•	AI can’t fix cultural or ownership gaps.

⸻

“AI Insights” Caveat
	•	AI often averages → results can feel like design-by-committee.
	•	Good reminder: don’t outsource expert judgment.

⸻

Giskard Demo Feedback
	•	Time & Events focus:
	•	Use calendar as input to log.
	•	Use calendar for time-blocking (“spend 20 mins on X”).
	•	Explore automatic task creation from events.
	•	Light gamification may help.
	•	Stickiness of calendars:
	•	Calendars = socially enforced (invitations).
	•	Avoid task backlog; calendar is always “blank.”
	•	Context engineering:
	•	Stronger data access + integration with note-takers.

⸻

PM in the Age of AI — Meetup Recap

Attendees: Derek, Geoff (ProductCamp), Nate, Jason, Adele (joined later), Charles.
Theme: How product management changes in the age of AI.

Market & Culture
	•	Jason: Compared US and Asia tech approaches.

	•	US: divergent exploration.
	•	Lens for adoption: execution focus vs divergent experimentation.

⸻

Talent Shape with AI
	•	AI won’t outperform top experts, and it won’t rescue the weakest.
	•	It primarily lifts the middle 90%.
	•	Shapes:
	•	T-shape → V-shape: AI makes you deeper in adjacent areas and broader overall.
	•	Debate: does it create a “bigger T” or a “sharper V”?
	•	Charles: personal sense is that AI sharpens into a V-shape.

⸻

Product Practice with AI
	•	PRDs → Prototypes: Faster validation cycles.
	•	Derek: Example GTM tools: Amplemarket + Clay.
	•	Feedback to Charles:
	•	Prototypes = forcing function + communication tool.
	•	Last mile remains:
	•	Quick Start docs at beginning + “Things to watch for” docs at end help.
	•	LLM prototypes: useful to say “close to vision, not worth fixing yet.”

⸻

LLM Risks & Controls
	•	More reasoning steps + more tool hops = higher drift risk.
	•	Strong PM oversight can control drift but can’t eliminate it.
	•	Some challenges remain structural:
	•	Example: PRDs still useful for handover across teams.
	•	AI can’t fix cultural or ownership gaps.

NVIDIA Small Models White Paper — Key Points
Core Thesis
Small language models (SLMs, < ~10B parameters) are good enough for many agentic AI tasks.


They offer major advantages in latency, cost, and deployability, making them better suited for large-scale, production agent systems.


LLMs remain necessary for open-ended reasoning and novel situations, but shouldn’t run every part of the pipeline.


Advantages of SLMs
Cost — inference is cheaper by 10–50× compared to LLMs.


Speed — lower latency makes interactive/real-time use feasible.


Deployability — easier to run on local or edge hardware; simpler to fine-tune and swap in/out.


Sustainability — reduced energy and infra burden.


Hybrid Architecture
Use SLMs for repetitive, structured errands (tool calls, JSON generation, routing, summarization).


Use LLMs as a fallback for high-novelty or ambiguous cases.


Goal: modular, composable agent pipelines where SLMs handle most traffic.


Conversion Process (LLM → SLM)
Collect logs of LLM usage.


Cluster recurring “agentic errands.”


Train or fine-tune SLMs per cluster.


Swap SLMs into pipeline with LLM fallback.


Iterate with evaluation and guardrails.


Barriers to Adoption
Ecosystem inertia: infra and culture built around LLMs.


Evaluation bias: benchmarks reward broad reasoning, favoring LLMs.


Trust gap: SLMs more brittle on edge cases, hallucinations more visible.


Operational complexity: orchestration with multiple models adds moving parts.


Risks & Limitations
Over-specialization can cause brittle failure on distribution shift.


Benchmarks may under-reflect real agentic workloads.


Without fallback/abstain mechanisms, errors can be catastrophic.


Takeaway
For agentic AI, small is beautiful: push high-volume, structured tasks to SLMs, reserve LLMs for rare or novel reasoning.


This hybrid approach reduces cost and latency while enabling new product patterns (continuous background checks, near-real-time monitoring)

tasks.title: Dead PM Meetup
tasks.description:
Notes from meetup:

PM in the Age of AI — Meetup Recap

Attendees: Derek, Geoff (ProductCamp), Nate, Jason, Adele (joined later), Charles.
Theme: How product management changes in the age of AI.

⸻

Market & Culture
	•	Jason: Compared US and Asia tech approaches.
	•	Asia: relentless execution and incrementalism.
	•	US: divergent exploration.
	•	Lens for adoption: execution focus vs divergent experimentation.

⸻

Talent Shape with AI
	•	AI won’t outperform top experts, and it won’t rescue the weakest.
	•	It primarily lifts the middle 90%.
	•	Shapes:
	•	T-shape → V-shape: AI makes you deeper in adjacent areas and broader overall.
	•	Debate: does it create a “bigger T” or a “sharper V”?
	•	Charles: personal sense is that AI sharpens into a V-shape.

⸻

Product Practice with AI
	•	PRDs → Prototypes: Faster validation cycles.
	•	Derek: Example GTM tools: Amplemarket + Clay.
	•	Feedback to Charles:
	•	Prototypes = forcing function + communication tool.
	•	Last mile remains:
	•	Quick Start docs at beginning + “Things to watch for” docs at end help.
	•	LLM prototypes: useful to say “close to vision, not worth fixing yet.”

⸻

LLM Risks & Controls
	•	More reasoning steps + more tool hops = higher drift risk.
	•	Strong PM oversight can control drift but can’t eliminate it.
	•	Some challenges remain structural:
	•	Example: PRDs still useful for handover across teams.
	•	AI can’t fix cultural or ownership gaps.

⸻

“AI Insights” Caveat
	•	AI often averages → results can feel like design-by-committee.
	•	Good reminder: don’t outsource expert judgment.

⸻

Giskard Demo Feedback
	•	Time & Events focus:
	•	Use calendar as input to log.
	•	Use calendar for time-blocking (“spend 20 mins on X”).
	•	Explore automatic task creation from events.
	•	Light gamification may help.
	•	Stickiness of calendars:
	•	Calendars = socially enforced (invitations).
	•	Avoid task backlog; calendar is always “blank.”
	•	Context engineering:
	•	Stronger data access + integration with note-takers.

⸻
